Here is a fun  Bloomberg Businessweek story about a guy named Andean Medjed=
ovic=C2=A0who hacked a decentralized finance project called Indexed Finance=
, taking about $16 million in a series of trades that (1) were allowed by I=
ndexed=E2=80=99s smart contracts but (2) Indexed=E2=80=99s founders clearly=
 didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0intend=C2=A0to allow. So they sued:On Dec. 9, nearly t=
wo months after the attack, Kellar and Day filed a lawsuit against Medjedov=
ic in Ontario, arguing that his actions amounted to fraud and that he shoul=
d be forced to return the tokens to their original owners. =E2=80=A6In thei=
r complaint, lawyers for Kellar and Day argued that two particular steps of=
 the attack violated statutes against market manipulation and computer hack=
ing. One was swapping almost all the UNI tokens out of the DEFI5 pool, the =
otherwise irrational trade that distorted the pricing such that Medjedovic =
could buy tokens out from under Indexed users, who were forced by the algor=
ithm to sell. =E2=80=9CThe only purpose of that trade was to mislead token =
holders to part with tokens on terms they never would have agreed to,=E2=80=
=9D says Stephen Aylward, a lawyer representing Kellar and Day. =E2=80=9CWe=
 say that=E2=80=99s a form of market manipulation.=E2=80=9D The same argume=
nt applied to Medjedovic=E2=80=99s interaction with the CC10 pool.The secon=
d illegal transaction, they argued, was when Medjedovic overwhelmed the poo=
l with free Sushi, thereby tricking the algorithm into letting him bypass t=
he size limit on certain trades. Aylward calls this =E2=80=9Can intentional=
 act by Andean to disable a security measure,=E2=80=89like disabling the se=
curity system at a bank.=E2=80=9D He argues that this falls under Canada=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9Cextremely broad=E2=80=9D legal definition of a hack, which=
 can be interpreted as =E2=80=9Csubverting the intended purpose of a comput=
er system.=E2=80=9DMedjedovic hasn=E2=80=99t officially responded to either=
 suit; he told me he doesn=E2=80=99t even have a lawyer in Ontario. But in =
our email exchanges, he argued that he=E2=80=99d executed a perfectly legal=
 series of trades. Nothing he did =E2=80=9Cinvolves getting access to a sys=
tem I was not allowed access into,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI did not ste=
al anyone=E2=80=99s private keys. I interacted with the smart contract acco=
rding to its very own publicly available rules. The people who lost interne=
t tokens in this trade were other people seeking to use the smart contract =
to their own advantage and taking on risky trading positions that they, app=
arently, did not fully understand.=E2=80=9D Medjedovic added that he=E2=80=
=99d taken on =E2=80=9Csubstantial risk=E2=80=9D in pursuing this strategy.=
 If he=E2=80=99d failed he would have lost =E2=80=9Ca pretty large chunk of=
 my portfolio.=E2=80=9DDon=E2=80=99t worry too much about the details there=
. The point is that Medjedovic did a couple of individually irrational tran=
sactions (buying UNI tokens for much more than the market price, selling Su=
shi tokens for much less than the market price) in order to manipulate the =
contract to give him more money. Is that market manipulation? Sure, I dunno=
, why not; if you do that in the US stock market then the Securities and Ex=
change Commission will at least look into it. A hallmark of market manipula=
tion is doing an individually irrational trade in one place in order to mak=
e money somewhere else. That isn=E2=80=99t a=C2=A0definition=C2=A0of market=
 manipulation =E2=80=94=C2=A0it is not illegal to do irrational trades =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but it is a rough guide to=C2=A0recognizing=C2=A0market manipul=
ation.=C2=A0On the other hand he didn=E2=80=99t do this in the stock market=
, the precedents here are slim, and, as he says, he =E2=80=9Cinteracted wit=
h the smart contract according to its very own publicly available rules.=E2=
=80=9D The subjective meaning of the smart contract and the objective code =
of the smart contract were different. I think it is possible for a judge =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0or for you and me =E2=80=94=C2=A0to know what the subjective=
 meaning was, to conclude =E2=80=9Cwhatever the smart contract actually all=
ows, it wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0supposed=C2=A0to allow this.=E2=80=9D As a form=
er lawyer and a traditional finance guy, I am used to that idea and not bot=
hered by it. But in the crypto world there are still, even now, code-is-law=
 types who think that the only thing a smart contract could mean is what it=
 says. In the crypto world, it is not at all clear that Medjedovic did anyt=
hing wrong.One other fun aspect of the story is what the Indexed developers=
 are up to:On the bright side, Day has a new cat, Katniss. And as painful a=
s the attack and its aftermath have been, it has brought attention: Kellar =
and Day are both fielding job offers in DeFi. Day is also applying to law s=
chools. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s not many people who can bridge that divide=
 between technical and legal frameworks,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CI figur=
ed I=E2=80=99ll do it myself.=E2=80=9DAround  here I  like to  say that, in=
 traditional finance, losing a lot of money can be good for your career: If=
 a trader loses a lot of money, it means that (1) someone trusted her to ta=
ke a lot of risk, (2) she was bold enough to actually take that risk, and (=
3) surely she learned some lessons and will be more careful next time. Cryp=
to has adopted that model too!
