Here is a theory of Elon Musk and Twitter Inc. that I have not seen anyone =
else write, so I am going to write it, even though I don=E2=80=99t really t=
hink it=E2=80=99s true.=09Elon Musk wants to buy Twitter, for some set of p=
ersonal, philosophical or political reasons. He is addicted to Twitter and =
wants to   improve the user experience for himself, he wants to optimize Tw=
itter to promote Tesla Inc.=C2=A0stock or right-wing politics, he has a pri=
ncipled commitment to free speech and wants to optimize Twitter for that, e=
tc.=09He has plenty of money to buy Twitter (he=E2=80=99s the richest perso=
n in the world) and does not care about the economics of the deal. (=E2=80=
=9CThis is not a way to sort of make money,=E2=80=9D  he has said, adding t=
hat he doesn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Ccare about the economics at all.=E2=80=9D) =
He wants Twitter for personal reasons and is willing and able to spend $46 =
billion for those reasons, even if he never gets back a cent.=09He is, howe=
ver, worried that someone might not=C2=A0let=C2=A0him buy Twitter. Maybe th=
e Securities and Exchange Commission, annoyed by his   securities-law viola=
tions in trying to buy Twitter, will somehow stop him. Maybe the Federal Tr=
ade Commission, annoyed by his   antitrust-law violations in trying to buy =
Twitter, will block the deal. Maybe some other regulator will find some oth=
er reason to stop him. Maybe Twitter shareholders will vote against the dea=
l, or maybe a few shareholders will=C2=A0sue to enjoin the deal because of =
some irregularity in the process. Maybe Twitter employees will quit en mass=
e because they don=E2=80=99t like him and his vision for Twitter, leaving h=
im with nothing to buy.=C2=A0=09So he is =09=09pretending not to want to bu=
y Twitter as a simple=C2=A0bit of reverse psychology. This way, everyone wh=
o dislikes him and didn=E2=80=99t want him to buy Twitter will be like =E2=
=80=9CI hate Elon Musk so much, it is imperative that he buy Twitter!=E2=80=
=9DAgain, I don=E2=80=99t think this is true, but I give it like =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A010% odds of being true? I think Premise 1 is mostly true (he wants to=
 own Twitter for mainly non-economic reasons), Premise 2 is mostly not (he =
does care about the economics, wants to syndicate his equity financing=C2=
=A0and is  feeling a bit strained by the crash in social-media stocks and T=
esla), Premise 3 is mostly not (no one is likely to block this deal), and t=
he conclusion is mostly wrong (he really is angling to pay a lower price). =
But I don=E2=80=99t have huge confidence in any of those views, and at this=
 point very little about Musk and Twitter would surprise me.So for instance=
 yesterday Insider broke a story that SpaceX paid a settlement over allegat=
ions that Musk offered to buy a flight attendant a horse in exchange for a =
sexual=C2=A0massage, and Musk tweeted that =E2=80=9Cit was clear that [Insi=
der=E2=80=99s] only goal was a hit [piece] to interfere with the Twitter ac=
quisition.=E2=80=9D[2] Which is a weird response! I do not think that this =
story will do anything at all to interfere with the Twitter acquisition, an=
d Musk has been trying very hard to interfere with that acquisition himself=
. He has spent much of the last week interfering with it! He just doesn=E2=
=80=99t want anyone=C2=A0else=C2=A0to interfere with it. He wants to close =
the deal, but he wants his critics to think he doesn=E2=80=99t want to, so =
they won=E2=80=99t try to stop him.Or: Three weeks ago,=C2=A0Twitter execut=
ives held an all-hands=C2=A0meetings with employees to, like, apologize for=
 selling the company to Musk and console them for the change in ownership. =
Morale had declined, employees were angry and worried about the Musk deal, =
and=C2=A0Twitter Chief Executive Officer Parag=C2=A0Agrawal tried to reassu=
re them that it would be okay:Agrawal concluded by asking employees to =E2=
=80=9Cembrace change.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s embrace change. Let=E2=
=80=99s embrace uncertainty,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIf we see this as a=
n opportunity, it will manifest as an opportunity. If we see this as doom a=
nd gloom, it will manifest as doom and gloom.=E2=80=9DYesterday Twitter exe=
cutives  held an all-hands meeting with employees to reassure them that the=
 deal was closing:Twitter Inc. executives told employees on Thursday that t=
he $44 billion deal to sell the company to billionaire Elon Musk is moving =
forward as planned, and that they won=E2=80=99t renegotiate the agreed-upon=
 price of $54.20 per share.=C2=A0Vijaya Gadde, Twitter=E2=80=99s top lawyer=
 and head of policy, also told workers at an all-hands meeting that there i=
s =E2=80=9Cno such thing as a deal being on hold,=E2=80=9D according to peo=
ple who attended the meeting.Morale had declined, employees were angry and =
worried about the Musk deal=C2=A0falling through, and they were happy to he=
ar that Musk will probably be buying the company after all =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
he thing that made them sad three weeks ago. What changed? Well, for one th=
ing, tech stocks fell, and the employees are probably more attached to thei=
r paychecks than they were three weeks ago. But for another thing, buying T=
witter at $54.20 now=C2=A0somehow=C2=A0seems like a=C2=A0loss=C2=A0for Musk=
.=C2=A0So if you don=E2=80=99t like Musk, now you are rooting for it to hap=
pen.=C2=A0He=E2=80=99s going to buy Twitter for $54.20 and show up for his =
first day of work=C2=A0as interim CEO and all the employees are going to be=
 ecstatic to see him.=C2=A0The ones who like him will be happy because they=
 like him, and the ones who hate him will be happy because they think he do=
esn=E2=80=99t want to be there. =E2=80=9CNow you are stuck with us, haha,=
=E2=80=9D they will say, pleased that they tricked him into buying Twitter.=
 But he wanted to buy Twitter!
