10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPAC SPAC SPAC</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A common enough structural feature in =
financial markets is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-lef=
t: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is a t=
hing.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Smart wealthy well-con=
nected insiders discover the thing and buy it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">The price goes up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">No=
rmal retail investors discover the thing and buy it.</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The smart wealthy well-connected insiders sell the thing=
 at high prices to the retail investors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Then the price goes down.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do=
n=E2=80=99t think that this is <em>the </em>general mechanism of financial =
markets or anything =E2=80=94=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t think that, like, =E2=80=
=9Cthe smart money=E2=80=9D is off buying one asset class while the rubes a=
re buying something else =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is definitely=C2=A0<em>a=C2=
=A0</em>mechanism. For instance this could roughly describe=C2=A0much of ve=
nture capital, where=C2=A0VCs put money into startups at low valuations, an=
d then those startups take off and go public at higher valuations. Or it de=
scribes some of crypto, where VCs make billions selling, for instance, <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27784498.284618/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTYvbm92b2dyYXR6L=
WdvZXMtc2lsZW50LW9uLXR3aXR0ZXItYWZ0ZXItdGVycmEtdXN0LWFuZC1sdW5hLXBsdW5nZT9j=
bXBpZD1CQkQwNTIwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV=
3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB1d85b3f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Luna tokens to retail</a> just before the=
y crash.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One amusing thing about the =
special-purpose acquisition company boom is that it kind of went the opposi=
te way? The way a SPAC works is that a sponsor =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally a w=
ell-connected successful financier or businessperson =E2=80=94 raises a pot=
 of money from public investors and then goes and looks for a private compa=
ny to take public using the pot of money. If she succeeds, the public inves=
tors end up owning the target company, and the sponsor gets a huge chunk of=
 shares almost for free. If she fails, the public investors get their money=
 back with a tiny amount of interest, and the sponsor is out of pocket for =
the costs (underwriting fees, lawyers, etc.) of doing the SPAC. Those costs=
 are trivial in comparison to the huge chunk of shares she will get for fre=
e in a successful deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they are not trivial in compariso=
n with=C2=A0<em>nothing</em>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There w=
as a huge boom in SPACs in 2020 and early 2021. Many retail investors piled=
 into SPACs. And because of the demand for SPACs, many sponsors piled into=
=C2=A0<em>raising=C2=A0</em>SPACs. They saw other sponsors getting rich by =
raising SPACs and finding targets, so they wanted in. And now there are a l=
ot of SPACs chasing not many deals, and proposed <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27784498.284618/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMzEvdGhlLXNlYy1pcy1jb21pbmctZm9yLXN=
wYWNzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdX=
JjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0e4e8512" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Securities and Exchange Commissio=
n rules</a> mean that it will be harder for those SPACs to do any deals. SP=
ACs are time-limited =E2=80=94=C2=A0generally they have to return their mon=
ey after two years if they don=E2=80=99t do a deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0and a bun=
ch of them are coming up on their expiration dates with no deals.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plenty of retail investors probably got burned buyin=
g SPACs,=C2=A0paying huge prices for shares in SPACs that took speculative =
companies public, only to see the shares drop when the companies didn=E2=80=
=99t perform. But the retail investors who piled in at the tail end of the =
boom just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sort of paid $10 for shares of SPACs that never di=
d anything and will return their $10 with interest? Meanwhile the=C2=A0<em>=
sponsors=C2=A0</em>who piled in at the tail end <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27784498.284618/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hc=
nRpY2xlcy9zdG9jay1zZWxsb2ZmLWNydW5jaGVzLXNwYWMtY3JlYXRvcnMtYXMtdGhleS1yYWNl=
LXRvLWZpbmQtZGVhbHMtMTE2NTI4NjYzODA_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB28bbe008" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">are holding the bag</a>:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An investor stampede out of risky trades is squee=
zing SPACs that are running out of time to find companies to take public, p=
otentially leaving their architects without deals and saddled with sizable =
losses. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A unique element of the SPAC ma=
rket is that shell companies=E2=80=99 creators typically have two years to =
find a company to take public, otherwise they must return money to investor=
s and forfeit the $5 million to $10 million on average that they pay to set=
 up the blank-check firms through lawyers and auditors and evaluate mergers=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because so many SPACs raised money during=
 the frenzy early last year, roughly 280 face deadlines in the first quarte=
r of 2023, figures from data provider SPAC Research show. If the current pa=
ce of SPAC deal making continues, analysts estimate that a large percentage=
 of those blank-check firms won=E2=80=99t find mergers. The merger window f=
or many SPACs is closing because it often takes months to find a deal and m=
any companies that previously might have considered such mergers are now el=
ecting to stay private, bankers say.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Creato=
rs of those SPACs and other insiders together are now expected by early nex=
t year to lose $1 billion or more=E2=80=94money known as =E2=80=9Cat-risk c=
apital=E2=80=9D that they have already spent setting up the SPACs and can n=
ever get back. (Of course, if the creators do strike deals, they stand to m=
ake several times their money on paper because of how those deals are struc=
tured.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a ticking tim=
e bomb,=E2=80=9D said Matt Simpson, managing partner at Wealthspring Capita=
l and a SPAC investor.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When we=
 first started talking about SPACs, early in the boom, <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27784498.284618/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMjcvc3BhY3MtYXJlbi10LWNoZWFwZ=
XItdGhhbi1pcG9zLXlldD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTIwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVt=
YWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1=
vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB23050291" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> I was baffled</a> =
by SPAC sponsors=E2=80=99 claims that the SPAC was an efficient way to cut =
out Wall Street and take companies public directly. My view was, no, SPACs =
are hugely lucrative for Wall Street banks; it=E2=80=99s just that they=E2=
=80=99re also lucrative for their sponsors, which makes them=C2=A0<em>more=
=C2=A0</em>expensive than a traditional initial public offering for issuers=
 and investors. (You=E2=80=99re paying fees to banks and sponsors, instead =
of just to banks.)=C2=A0But actually the result is funnier than that: The S=
PAC boom might have been, among other things, a $1 billion transfer of valu=
e from SPAC sponsors to Wall Street bankers and lawyers. Wall Street got pa=
id $1 billion of fees to=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>take companies public. Oops=
!</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpaddi=
ng=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
